<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1323,1671,1898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,418,1671,1697]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Description:</emphasis>
Shell oval, high (I H/L= 
<number box="[722,751,1672,1698]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="85.0">85</number>
± 
<number box="[784,801,1672,1698]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
), medium to large size (maximum observed L = 
<quantity box="[313,421,1712,1738]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.35" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="5.35">5.35 mm</quantity>
), not inflated (Ci = 
<number box="[651,680,1712,1738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="59.0">59</number>
± 
<number box="[711,728,1712,1738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="5.0">5</number>
). Dorsal and ventral margins markedly curved, the anterior margin slopes evenly to the anterior end, which is slightly projected. Posterior end short, rounded, somewhat oblique in adults, markedly truncated in smaller specimens (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 3 A – C" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1535,1559]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,1032,1510]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[264,1323,1032,1511]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 3 A – C. Pisidium lebruni. A. Lectotype (MNHN, Paris), outer lateral view of right valve. B, C. Paralectotypes (MNHN, Paris). B. Right valve, inner view. C. Left valve, outer view. Scale bars: A – C = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174350/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,278,1832,1858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
A, C
</figureCitation>
). Beaks wide at base, very low, slightly projected over dorsal margin, located at 
<number box="[1270,1299,1832,1858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="57.0">57</number>
± 
<number box="[264,300,1872,1898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="1.4">1.4</number>
% of L (
<figureCitation box="[405,533,1872,1898]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 A – C" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1535,1559]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,1032,1510]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[264,1323,1032,1511]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 3 A – C. Pisidium lebruni. A. Lectotype (MNHN, Paris), outer lateral view of right valve. B, C. Paralectotypes (MNHN, Paris). B. Right valve, inner view. C. Left valve, outer view. Scale bars: A – C = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174350/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
Fig. 
<number box="[460,474,1872,1898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
A, C
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,284,990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Hinge plate moderately strong, hinge line short (Hil/L= 
<number box="[982,1011,284,310]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="53.0">53</number>
± 
<number box="[1046,1061,284,310]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="5.0">5</number>
) and markedly curve. Ligament pit enclosed, short, deep; ligament internal, long (Li= 
<number box="[1029,1058,324,350]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="21.0">21</number>
± 
<number box="[1092,1109,324,350]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
), not visible from exterior except from a quite slender gap. Hinge: left valve: cardinal teeth thin, the outer (C 
<number box="[293,309,404,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
) overlapping C 
<number box="[492,506,404,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
at the posterior third; anterior (A 
<number box="[899,914,404,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
) and posterior (P 
<number box="[1118,1133,404,430]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="2.0">2</number>
) laterals strong, short, cusps sub-central. Right valve: cardinal tooth (C 
<number box="[932,946,444,470]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
) delicate, anterior end slender, curved, shorter than the posterior end which is slightly expanded in a triangular sulcated cup; anterior and posterior lateral teeth well developed, the inners (A 
<number box="[1075,1085,524,550]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
and P 
<number box="[1163,1174,524,550]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="1.0">1</number>
) solid, long, with slightly displaced cusps; the outer laterals (A 
<number box="[877,890,564,590]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
and P 
<number box="[973,987,564,590]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
) strong but reduced in size (
<figureCitation box="[273,364,604,630]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 A – C" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1535,1559]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,1032,1510]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[264,1323,1032,1511]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 3 A – C. Pisidium lebruni. A. Lectotype (MNHN, Paris), outer lateral view of right valve. B, C. Paralectotypes (MNHN, Paris). B. Right valve, inner view. C. Left valve, outer view. Scale bars: A – C = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174350/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[327,342,604,630]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="3.0">3</number>
B
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,284,990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,437,644,670]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Anatomy:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[449,532,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Mantle</emphasis>
: only anal mantle opening present. Inner radial mantle muscles weak; 
<number box="[341,386,684,710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8</number>
bundles of few fibres were observed (
<figureCitation box="[837,932,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 A – D" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,849,1302]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[264,1323,816,1310]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 4 A – D. Pisidium lebruni, anatomy. A. Gross anatomy. B. Left nephridium in dorsal view. C. Nephridia in lateral view, open type at left, closed type at right. D. Inner view of inner demibranch showing the position of brood sac in early stage of development. (aa. anterior adductor muscle; al: ascending lamellae; as: anal siphon; bs: brood; dl: descending lamellae; dln: dorsal lobe of nephridium; f. foot; h: heart; irm: inner radial mantle muscles; ld: left demibranch; ll: lateral loop of nephridium; n: nephridium; pa: posterior adductor muscle; pd: pericardial duct; pr: pedal retractor muscle; rd: right demibranch)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[892,908,684,710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). Scars of the inner radial mantle muscles, slightly visible, merged with or immediately over the pallial line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,284,990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[312,452,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Nephridium</emphasis>
: Lateral loop visible from dorsal view, dorsal lobe of nephridium subquadrangular, proximal part of the nephridium, the pericardial duct, usually not visible (closed 
<typeStatus box="[359,411,844,870]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">type</typeStatus>
) from dorsal side (
<figureCitation box="[647,817,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 A – D" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,849,1302]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[264,1323,816,1310]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 4 A – D. Pisidium lebruni, anatomy. A. Gross anatomy. B. Left nephridium in dorsal view. C. Nephridia in lateral view, open type at left, closed type at right. D. Inner view of inner demibranch showing the position of brood sac in early stage of development. (aa. anterior adductor muscle; al: ascending lamellae; as: anal siphon; bs: brood; dl: descending lamellae; dln: dorsal lobe of nephridium; f. foot; h: heart; irm: inner radial mantle muscles; ld: left demibranch; ll: lateral loop of nephridium; n: nephridium; pa: posterior adductor muscle; pd: pericardial duct; pr: pedal retractor muscle; rd: right demibranch)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[705,720,844,870]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
A, B, C
</figureCitation>
right), except in few cases (open 
<typeStatus box="[1236,1287,844,870]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">type</typeStatus>
of nephridium) (
<figureCitation box="[425,513,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 A – D" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,849,1302]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[264,1323,816,1310]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 4 A – D. Pisidium lebruni, anatomy. A. Gross anatomy. B. Left nephridium in dorsal view. C. Nephridia in lateral view, open type at left, closed type at right. D. Inner view of inner demibranch showing the position of brood sac in early stage of development. (aa. anterior adductor muscle; al: ascending lamellae; as: anal siphon; bs: brood; dl: descending lamellae; dln: dorsal lobe of nephridium; f. foot; h: heart; irm: inner radial mantle muscles; ld: left demibranch; ll: lateral loop of nephridium; n: nephridium; pa: posterior adductor muscle; pd: pericardial duct; pr: pedal retractor muscle; rd: right demibranch)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[480,495,884,910]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
C
</figureCitation>
left).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,284,990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[312,367,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Gill:</emphasis>
Only inner demibranch present (
<figureCitation box="[798,947,924,950]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 A – D" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,849,1302]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[264,1323,816,1310]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 4 A – D. Pisidium lebruni, anatomy. A. Gross anatomy. B. Left nephridium in dorsal view. C. Nephridia in lateral view, open type at left, closed type at right. D. Inner view of inner demibranch showing the position of brood sac in early stage of development. (aa. anterior adductor muscle; al: ascending lamellae; as: anal siphon; bs: brood; dl: descending lamellae; dln: dorsal lobe of nephridium; f. foot; h: heart; irm: inner radial mantle muscles; ld: left demibranch; ll: lateral loop of nephridium; n: nephridium; pa: posterior adductor muscle; pd: pericardial duct; pr: pedal retractor muscle; rd: right demibranch)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[862,877,924,950]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
A, D
</figureCitation>
). Brood sac developing from descending lamellae in upper position (
<figureCitation box="[724,819,964,990]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 A – D" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1326,1350]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,849,1302]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[264,1323,816,1310]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 4 A – D. Pisidium lebruni, anatomy. A. Gross anatomy. B. Left nephridium in dorsal view. C. Nephridia in lateral view, open type at left, closed type at right. D. Inner view of inner demibranch showing the position of brood sac in early stage of development. (aa. anterior adductor muscle; al: ascending lamellae; as: anal siphon; bs: brood; dl: descending lamellae; dln: dorsal lobe of nephridium; f. foot; h: heart; irm: inner radial mantle muscles; ld: left demibranch; ll: lateral loop of nephridium; n: nephridium; pa: posterior adductor muscle; pd: pericardial duct; pr: pedal retractor muscle; rd: right demibranch)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/174351/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[779,795,964,990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" value="4.0">4</number>
D
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
